{"TopicId":193475,"ForumId":16,"TopicTitle":"How to decrease kerbal eva drag?","CreatedByName":"Alexoff","CreatedById":145774,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T12:07:29Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"Alexoff","CreatedById":145774,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T12:07:29Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u0027m trying to make small craft for Laythe. So i decided to make it with external command seat. But when I tried to ascend my kerbal ate plenty of \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Delta-V\u0022\u003EdV\u003C/abbr\u003E by a huge drag. In fact my kerbanaut is covered up with another part from the airflow and should not be the most draggy thing on the craft. So, I know that if I put seat to small service bay it\u0027s some kind of solution, but cargobay is quite heavy and has some drag too. Is there any other ways to reduce kerbal drag by some covering?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"linuxgurugamer","CreatedById":129964,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T12:09:19Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow about a picture to show us what you have?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Fraktal","CreatedById":184990,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T12:24:17Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223777770\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022193475\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221588162049\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022145774\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Alexoff\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n15 minutes ago, Alexoff said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIn fact my kerbanaut is covered up with another part from the airflow and should not be the most draggy thing on the craft.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAs far as I\u0027m aware, KSP does not model airflow obstruction on radially attached parts.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Alexoff","CreatedById":145774,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T12:45:47Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223777772\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022193475\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221588162159\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129964\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022linuxgurugamer\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n30 minutes ago, linuxgurugamer said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow about a picture to show us what you have?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo I have a lot of variation of Stratzenblitz Laythe ascending craft like this [4:48]\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedVideo\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 height=\u0022270\u0022 width=\u0022480\u0022 data-embed-src=\u0022https://www.youtube.com/embed/LT2Fggr_LWQ?feature=oembed\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut after some nerfing spark engine (and maybe changing physics) after several patches this craft is not so effective.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223777778\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022193475\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221588163057\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022184990\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Fraktal\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n20 minutes ago, Fraktal said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAs far as I\u0027m aware, KSP does not model airflow obstruction on radially attached parts.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo no way?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Fraktal","CreatedById":184990,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T16:41:06Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223777785\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022193475\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221588164347\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022145774\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Alexoff\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n3 hours ago, Alexoff said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo no way?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nCargo bay, service bay or \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Ferram Aerospace Research (mod)\u0022\u003EFAR\u003C/abbr\u003E.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Linkageless","CreatedById":201088,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T20:22:59Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u0027m guessing the large drag you are seeing is either on the seat or the Kerbal.\u00A0 I do know that a kerbal with deployed chute has the drag and lift applied from their backpack rather than where the chute is.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIf you haven\u0027t already, I suggest going into the alt-F12 screen and activating Physics\u0026gt;Aero\u0026gt;Display Aero Data in Action Menus.\u00A0 That way you should be able to get an objective measure of which parts are giving the most drag at any one moment rather than just going by the F12 drag lines.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"CBase","CreatedById":189476,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-04-29T23:38:40Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223777885\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022193475\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221588178466\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022184990\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Fraktal\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n6 hours ago, Fraktal said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nCargo bay, service bay\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u002B Fairings\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nEspecially if you use procedural fairings or tweakscale to create smaller version just around seat this is most light weight solution. Do not forget to equip helmet on launch \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:rolleyes:\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_rolleyes.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:rolleyes:\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}